# OS component rules

Components under `src/os/` implement the Sprawl operating system
metaphor. They are higher-level than primitives and carry additional
constraints.

## State ownership

- OS components do NOT own window manager state. They receive it as
  props from `neuromancer` (the window manager package in Burning
  Chrome).
- A `<Window>` component renders a window. It does not decide where
  the window lives, its z-index, or whether it's focused. Those are
  kernel concerns.
- This separation is critical for testability and for the multi-runtime
  app loader.

## Required slots

Every OS component exposes named slots via `data-slot`:
- `<Window>`: `chrome`, `titlebar`, `controls`, `body`, `resize-handle`
- `<Taskbar>`: `start`, `items`, `tray`, `clock`
- `<Dock>`: `items`, `separator`

Consumers theme these via `[data-slot="..."]` selectors.

## Accessibility

- Windows must trap focus when modal, release when not. Use Radix
  `FocusScope`.
- Every interactive OS element has a keyboard equivalent (Cmd+W to
  close, arrow keys to navigate taskbar, etc.).
- Screen readers must announce window open/close and focus changes.

## Animation

- Use `motion` tokens from `tokens/motion.ts`.
- Respect `prefers-reduced-motion` — this is enforced by a test.
- Framer Motion is allowed for OS components only (primitives stay
  dependency-free).